        "trailText":"<strong>Lola Okolosie:</strong> Teachers are conflicted over many of Michael Gove's policies. But we are in no doubt as to his disrespect for our profession and the damage that causes",
        "headline":"Teachers do not take the decision to strike lightly",
        "body":"<p>The derision with which teachers are treated in much of the rightwing press creates the impression that it is our fault it's all gone to pot. Politicians believe the remedy is to throw more policies at the \"problem\". Meanwhile, teachers themselves are silenced in the cacophony of condemnation.</p><p>Today's co-ordinated <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/oct/17/teachers-strike-pay-thousands-schools-nasuwt\" title=\"\">strike action by the NUT and the NASUWT</a> seeks to protect our pensions and address the dismantling of our national pay system and proposals for a longer school day and year. In short, we are looking to be heard.</p><p>A couple of weeks ago the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development revealed that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/oct/08/england-young-people-league-table-basic-skills-oecd\" title=\"\">England \"is the only country in the developed world where the generation approaching retirement is more literate and numerate than the youngest adults</a>\". Some will have found the results confusing. How, at a time of year-on-year increases in the level of GCSE pass rates could we have such levels of illiteracy and innumeracy? Were poor teaching and teachers responsible? Some blame can rightly be apportioned here. Similarly, our fixation with GCSEs and league tables deserves to share in the opprobrium: it has had dire consequences for some of our young. Students in need of basic literacy and numeracy skills have been left behind by a culture which, as a result of government policy, funnelled all effort into the same narrow examination route. Teachers I have worked with over the past six years have been ringing this alarm bell to deaf ears.</p><p>Today's strike action leaves many teachers, myself included, oscillating between inertia and action. Will it serve only to alienate us from the public? How best do we fight for our rights in a climate where, it seems, a race to the bottom is a given reality? What would the acceptable public \"face\" of our strike action look like? We can begin by injecting nuance into our arguments, muddying the clear waters the education secretary, Michael Gove, insists on seeing. I am conflicted by the polarising of positions we are witnessing between the teaching unions and Gove. As a person of the left I cannot abandon my commitment to what the unions stand for. Yet I can see merit in some of Gove's ideas. Denied space in which to voice this or any other position, teachers are left with no choice but to take to the streets.</p><p>Gove's policies are often ideological, rushed and based on little evidence. They have helped to create dangerously low teacher morale. Yet under him we have seen a couple of policies that progressives can be happy with. They stand out among the many that are issued and then, thankfully, scrapped. When, a few weeks ago, Gove's department announced what was in essence the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/sep/29/headteachers-criticise-new-rules-gcse-exams\" title=\"\">scrapping of GCSE resits</a>, I and others begrudgingly admitted that this, perhaps, wasn't all that bad. Yes, the timing of the seismic shift – mid-term, weeks before the November GCSE entries – was a perfect illustration of Gove's disrespect for the profession. He might as well have said: \"To hell with schools, pupils and parents, I can make changes even when courses have already begun.\"</p><p>In spite of the above, many approved of the reform. Even the most liberal of teachers would concede that resits were open to abuse. Yet the problem was not of our making. It is successive governments that have instituted what one colleague calls an \"endless obsession with GCSE results and league tables\". It is disingenuous to accuse schools of \"gaming\" the system when the stakes are so high.</p><p>The controversy over resits in some ways best exemplifies how battlelines cannot easily be drawn. As a profession we perhaps need to instigate an open conversation with the public about the fact that some teachers, a minority, should not be in a classroom.</p><p>The education secretary has expertly played his hand over this particular policy. The unions are doing a disservice to our young by supporting incompetent and under-performing teachers, or so the argument goes. For their part the unions overlook the reality that a minority of teachers are under-performing.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/apr/08/schools-performance-pay-teachers-education\" title=\"\">Performance-related pay </a>is, however, not the answer. Evidence the policy will improve standards is inconclusive. Yet the agenda remains. Such populism ignores teacher's warnings that pay based on performance will damage the collaborative ethos many schools have in place and lead to a toxic competitiveness from which students will suffer most.</p><p>Contrary to popular belief, choosing to strike won't be easy or clear-cut. Many, anxious about the public perception, will nevertheless maintain the picket line because of the continued unwillingness by the government to either listen to teachers or view us as legitimate participants in the education debate. Teachers will take action despite being worried that in striking we merely give Gove more rope with which to hang us.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420232888|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|c04e97130fb7aa2ce0a23b9745a0e02085f5a12f -->",
